"Timmreck C., Graf H.-F., Lorenz S.J., Niemeier U., Zanchettin D., Matei D., Jungclaus J.H., Crowley T.J.","Aerosol size confines climate response to volcanic super-eruptions",2010,"Geophysical Research Letters","37","24", L24705,"","",,,10.1029/2010GL045464,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-78650899956&partnerID=40&md5=deff5920f35e81b293682b9af13c5e47","Max-Planck Institute for Meteorology, Bundesstr. 53, D-20146 Hamburg, Germany; Centre Atmospheric Science, University of Cambridge, Lensfield Road, Cambridge CB2 1EW, United Kingdom; School of GeoSciences, University of Edinburgh, West Main Road, Edinburgh EH9 3JY, United Kingdom","Timmreck, C., Max-Planck Institute for Meteorology, Bundesstr. 53, D-20146 Hamburg, Germany; Graf, H.-F., Centre Atmospheric Science, University of Cambridge, Lensfield Road, Cambridge CB2 1EW, United Kingdom; Lorenz, S.J., Max-Planck Institute for Meteorology, Bundesstr. 53, D-20146 Hamburg, Germany; Niemeier, U., Max-Planck Institute for Meteorology, Bundesstr. 53, D-20146 Hamburg, Germany; Zanchettin, D., Max-Planck Institute for Meteorology, Bundesstr. 53, D-20146 Hamburg, Germany; Matei, D., Max-Planck Institute for Meteorology, Bundesstr. 53, D-20146 Hamburg, Germany; Jungclaus, J.H., Max-Planck Institute for Meteorology, Bundesstr. 53, D-20146 Hamburg, Germany; Crowley, T.J., School of GeoSciences, University of Edinburgh, West Main Road, Edinburgh EH9 3JY, United Kingdom","Extremely large volcanic eruptions have been linked to global climate change, biotic turnover, and, for the Younger Toba Tuff (YTT) eruption 74,000 years ago, near-extinction of modern humans. One of the largest uncertainties of the climate effects involves evolution and growth of aerosol particles. A huge atmospheric concentration of sulfate causes higher collision rates, larger particle sizes, and rapid fall out, which in turn greatly affects radiative feedbacks. We address this key process by incorporating the effects of aerosol microphysical processes into an Earth System Model. The temperature response is shorter (9-10 years) and three times weaker (-3.5 K at maximum globally) than estimated before, although cooling could still have reached -12 K in some midlatitude continental regions after one year. The smaller response, plus its geographic patchiness, suggests that most biota may have escaped threshold extinction pressures from the eruption. © 2010 by the American Geophysical Union.",,"Atmospheric aerosols; Volcanoes; Aerosol particles; Aerosol size; Atmospheric concentration; Climate effects; Collision rate; Earth system model; Global climate changes; Key process; Larger particle sizes; Microphysical process; Midlatitudes; Temperature response; Volcanic eruptions; Climate change; atmospheric chemistry; biota; climate change; climate effect; cooling; extinction; fallout; global climate; numerical model; particle size; radiation budget; sulfate; uncertainty analysis; volcanic eruption",,,,,,"Ambrose, S.H., Late Pleistocene human population bottlenecks, volcanic winter, and differentiation of modern humans (1998) J. Hum. Evol., 34, pp. 623-651; Balter, M., Of two minds about Toba's impact (2010) Science, 237, pp. 1187-1188; Bekki, S., Oxidation of volcanic SO<inf>2</inf>: A sink for stratospheric OH and H<inf>2</inf>O (1995) Geophys. Res. Lett, 22, pp. 913-916; Bekki, S., Pyle, J.A., Zhong, W., Toumi, R., Haigh, J.D., Pyle, D.M., The role of microphysical and chemical processes in prolonging the climate forcing of the Toba Eruption (1996) Geophys. Res. Lett, 23, pp. 2669-2672; Chesner, C.A., Luhr, J., Melt inclusion study of the Toba Tuffs, Sumatra, Indonesia (2010) J. Volcanol. Geotherm. Res., , doi:10.1016/j.jvolgeores.2010.06.001, in press; Chesner, C.A., Rose, W.I., Deino, A., Drake, R., Westgate, J.A., Eruptive history of Earth's largest Quaternary caldera (Toba, Indonesia) clarified (1991) Geology, 19, pp. 200-203; Haslam, M., Petraglia, M., Comment on ""environmental impact of the 73 ka Toba 